  7  /-!
  8  # lint command
  9  This file defines the following user commands to spot common mistakes in the code.
 10  * `#lint`: check all declarations in the current file
 11  * `#lint_mathlib`: check all declarations in mathlib (so excluding core or other projects,
 12    and also excluding the current file)
 13  * `#lint_all`: check all declarations in the environment (the current file and all
 14    imported files)
 15  
 16  The following linters are run by default:
 17  1.  `unused_arguments` checks for unused arguments in declarations.
 18  2.  `def_lemma` checks whether a declaration is incorrectly marked as a def/lemma.
 19  3.  `dup_namespce` checks whether a namespace is duplicated in the name of a declaration.
 20  4.  `ge_or_gt` checks whether ≥/> is used in the declaration.
 21  5.  `instance_priority` checks that instances that always apply have priority below default.
 22  6.  `doc_blame` checks for missing doc strings on definitions and constants.
 23  7.  `has_inhabited_instance` checks whether every type has an associated `inhabited` instance.
 24  8.  `impossible_instance` checks for instances that can never fire.
 25  9.  `incorrect_type_class_argument` checks for arguments in [square brackets] that are not classes.
 26  10. `dangerous_instance` checks for instances that generate type-class problems with metavariables.
 27  
 28  Another linter, `doc_blame_thm`, checks for missing doc strings on lemmas and theorems.
 29  This is not run by default.
 30  
 31  The command `#list_linters` prints a list of the names of all available linters.
 32  
 33  You can append a `*` to any command (e.g. `#lint_mathlib*`) to omit the slow tests (4).
 34  
 35  You can append a `-` to any command (e.g. `#lint_mathlib-`) to run a silent lint
 36  that suppresses the output of passing checks.
 37  A silent lint will fail if any test fails.
 38  
 39  You can append a sequence of linter names to any command to run extra tests, in addition to the
 40  default ones. e.g. `#lint doc_blame_thm` will run all default tests and `doc_blame_thm`.
 41  
 42  You can append `only name1 name2 ...` to any command to run a subset of linters, e.g.
 43  `#lint only unused_arguments`
 44  
 45  You can add custom linters by defining a term of type `linter` in the `linter` namespace.
 46  A linter defined with the name `linter.my_new_check` can be run with `#lint my_new_check`
 47  or `lint only my_new_check`.
 48  If you add the attribute `@[linter]` to `linter.my_new_check` it will run by default.
 49  
 50  Adding the attribute `@[nolint]` to a declaration omits it from all linter checks.
 51  
 52  ## Tags
 53  sanity check, lint, cleanup, command, tactic

296  library_note "lower instance priority"
297  "Certain instances always apply during type-class resolution. For example, the instance
298  `add_comm_group.to_add_group {α} [add_comm_group α] : add_group α` applies to all type-class
299  resolution problems of the form `add_group _`, and type-class inference will then do an
300  exhaustive search to find a commutative group. These instances take a long time to fail.
301  Other instances will only apply if the goal has a certain shape. For example
302  `int.add_group : add_group ℤ` or
303  `add_group.prod {α β} [add_group α] [add_group β] : add_group (α × β)`. Usually these instances
304  will fail quickly, and when they apply, they are almost the desired instance.
305  For this reason, we want the instances of the second type (that only apply in specific cases) to
306  always have higher priority than the instances of the first type (that always apply).
307  See also #1561.
308  
309  Therefore, if we create an instance that always applies, we set the priority of these instances to
310  100 (or something similar, which is below the default value of 1000)."
311  
312  library_note "default priority"
313  "Instances that always apply should be applied after instances that only apply in specific cases,
314  see note [lower instance priority] above.
315  
316  Classes that use the `extends` keyword automatically generate instances that always apply.
317  Therefore, we set the priority of these instances to 100 (or something similar, which is below the
318  default value of 1000) using `set_option default_priority 100`.
319  We have to put this option inside a section, so that the default priority is the default
320  1000 outside the section."
321
